{"text": "wave superconductor is most preferable. The second requirement is the existence of spinless\n\nfermions, which obviously do not occur naturally in solid state systems. One possible way\n\nout is the application of a Zeeman\n\neld to the electrons, Vz\u001bz, whereVzis the strength of\n\nthe Zeeman\n\neld and \u001bzis a Pauli spin matrix. Since the energy of the electrons in the\n\nparallel and anti-parallel direction to the Zeeman\n\neld is di\u000berent, this would lead to a shift\n\nof the parallel and anti-parallel energy bands. If now the Fermi energy could be tuned to\n\nfall in the lower band (Fig. 2), we would have spin-polarized fermions on the Fermi surface.\n\nFor the purposes of realizing MZMs, spin-polarized fermions are just as good as spinless\n\nfermions because in both cases the de\n\nnition of the Bogoliubov operator does not involve\n\nmixing of di\u000berent spins. One could now think of inducing s-wave superconductivity on the\n\nFermi surface, but this is impossible because the spins of the electrons at opposite momenta\n\nkand\u0000kon the Fermi surface are exactly aligned. To work around this problem one could\n\nthink of electrons having a strong Rashba spin-orbit coupling \u000b(~ \u001b\u0002~ p)\u0001^z, where\u000bis the\n\nstrength of the Rashba coupling. Due to the combined e\u000bects of \u000bandVz, the spins of the\n\nelectrons make a constant angle with the momenta on the Fermi surface. Since the spins\n\nof the electrons at momenta kand\u0000kon the Fermi surface are no longer exactly aligned\n\n29\n\nFIG. 2. Left: Fermi surface in a Zeeman-shifted spin-polarized band. Inducing s-wave super-\n\nconductivity on the Fermi surface is impossible in this case because the spins of the electrons at\n\nopposite momenta ( kand\u0000k) are aligned. Right: Fermi surface in a Zeeman-shifted spin-polarized\n\nband in the presence of Rashba spin-orbit coupling.", "embedding": [0.0043043485, 0.009343939, 0.009112768, -0.001958638, -0.0